<paragraph blockId="23.[189,1399,369,681]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
The distribution information provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman" box="[668,948,369,396]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref265860" refString="Hayman R. W., Misonne X. &amp; Verheyen W. N. 1966. The bats of the Congo and of Rwanda and Burundi. Annalen van het Koninklijk Museum voor Midden Afrika, Zoologische Wetenschappen, Ser. 8, 154: 1 - 105." type="journal article" year="1966">
Hayman 
<emphasis box="[772,829,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al.</emphasis>
(1966: 30
</bibRefCitation>
, map 17) suggested that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="E. Geoffroy" baseAuthorityYear="1810" box="[1228,1398,370,395]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Rousettus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aegyptiacus">
<emphasis box="[1228,1398,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">R. aegyptiacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only occurred along the eastern border of the 
<collectingCountry box="[741,801,405,431]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">DRC</collectingCountry>
(Ituri, Nord- and Sud-Kivu Provinces) and in the extreme south (Haut-Katanga Province) and the extreme west (Kongo Central Province). However, RBINS 12932 and 12933, reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hayman" box="[649,948,476,503]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref265860" refString="Hayman R. W., Misonne X. &amp; Verheyen W. N. 1966. The bats of the Congo and of Rwanda and Burundi. Annalen van het Koninklijk Museum voor Midden Afrika, Zoologische Wetenschappen, Ser. 8, 154: 1 - 105." type="journal article" year="1966">
Hayman 
<emphasis box="[757,817,476,502]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">et al.</emphasis>
(1966: 30)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Bergmans" box="[1008,1258,476,503]" firstAuthor="Bergmans" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="79 - 126" refId="ref257439" refString="Bergmans W. 1994. Taxonomy and biogeography of African fruit bats (Mammalia, Megachiroptera). 4. The genus Rousettus Gray, 1821. Beaufortia 44 (4): 79 - 126. Available from http: // www. repository. naturalis. nl / document / 548564 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1994">Bergmans (1994: 90)</bibRefCitation>
from Kivu, were actually from Buta (Bas-Uélé Province; Tom Geerinckx, pers. comm.). More recently collected specimens further extend the occurrence of this species to the west of the 
<collectingCountry box="[1077,1137,548,574]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">DRC</collectingCountry>
(Kisangani, Boende). These records indicate that two subspecies might occur in CRB: 
<emphasis box="[927,1007,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">leachii</emphasis>
in the eastern part of the 
<collectingCountry box="[1291,1351,584,610]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">DRC</collectingCountry>
and in 
<collectingCountry box="[219,315,619,645]" name="Rwanda" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Rwanda</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[373,472,619,645]" name="Burundi" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Burundi</collectingCountry>
, and 
<emphasis box="[534,633,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">unicolor</emphasis>
in the western part of the country. The subspecific assignment of the specimens from the intermediairy localities remains uncertain.
</paragraph>
